In philosophy, '''animalism''' is a theory according to which humans are animals.<ref>Eric T. Olson (2007) ''What are we?: a study in personal ontology'', Oxford University Press, section 2.1.</ref> The concept of animalism is advocated by philosophers [[Eric T. Olson (philosopher)|Eric T. Olson]], Paul Snowdon, Stephan Blatti, and [[David Wiggins]].<ref name=garrett> Brian Garrett, ''Personal Identity and Self-Consciousness''. Routledge, 1998. 137 pages. {{ISBN|0-415-16573-3}}</ref><ref>Blatti, Stephan and Snowdon, Paul (eds.) ''Animalism: New Essays on Persons, Animals, & Identity'', Oxford University Press, 2016.</ref><ref>Snowdon, Paul ''Persons, Animals, Ourselves'', Oxford University Press, 2017.</ref>

